##Why did the Fed's emergency rate cut fail? Market fears and the spread of the virus are hard to contain

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

On the one hand, monetary policy is already loose, interest rates are already low, and there is little room for policy manoeuvre. On the other hand, market fears and the spread of the virus have not stopped. The fight against the epidemic has only just begun, and there are no obvious signs of financial stability

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
By Jin Yan, CAIJING correspondent, Washington

Editor | Susie

Fed Chairman Powell unexpectedly cut the federal funds rate by 50 basis points to between 1% and 1.25% at a news conference on March 3, local time, under pressure from both the outbreak and the markets, cut The excess reserve ratio (Ioer) by 50 basis points to 1.1 per cent. In response to the risks to economic activity posed by the NCP epidemic. It was the first emergency rate cut since the 2008 financial crisis and the biggest since then.

Stocks rose across the board on March 2, with the Dow rebounding from a seven-session decline to its biggest one-day gain in more than a decade as investors bet that central banks could stabilise markets. Powell was decisive, pointing out that the interest rate cuts were intended to help the economy stay strong during the crisis; that job growth was solid and wage growth continued; and that the virus and the response would drag down economic activity for some time We will continue to act to keep the economy strong, using tools and actions to support it as appropriate. A cut in interest rates would boost confidence among households and businesses; no other measures have been considered; a cut in interest rates would not solve the supply chain problem, but it would avoid a tightening of financial conditions.

President Donald Trump took to twitter shortly after the Fed cut, calling for more easing. Though Bowie, the Fed chairman, hinted in a Feb. 28 statement that the Fed was prepared to cut interest rates in an effort to mitigate the effects of the potential public health crisis and the widening global economic slowdown on the U.S. economy. But the Fed's move was a big surprise because it was not on the Fed's schedule for the full-year meeting of the Federal Open Market Committee, which was scheduled for March 17-18.

However, to the surprise of some investors, U.S. stocks continued their volatile trend on March 3 after the Fed's strong response, with all three major U.S. stock indexes falling more than 1% after a narrow opening high, then the Fed cut the benchmark interest rate by 50 basis points to stimulate the straight-line increase of more than 1.2% , then deep down, the Dow fell from a high of nearly 1,400 points after a small rebound, but still as much as 800 points.

The S & P 500 index ended the day down 86.86, or 2.81 percent, at 3,003.37. The Dow Jones Industrial Average ended the day down 785.91, or 2.94 percent, at 25,917.41. The Nasdaq Composite Index ended the day down 268.08, or 2.99 percent, at 8,684.09. Big U.S. tech stocks were lower overall, with apple down 3.18% , Amazon down 2.3% , netflix down 3.22% , google down 3.51% , Facebook down 5.37% and Microsoft down 4.79% .

The Fed's emergency rate cut, seen by market participants as a response to investor concerns, should have helped to stabilise market expectations. But at the same time, such a rare move by the Fed suggests the severity of the current market and epidemic problems. Therefore, in the epidemic situation further clarity, the market panic will not be immediately removed.

The number of cases reported outside China in the past 24 hours has been almost nine times higher than in China, the WHO said on March 2. Spread of the epidemic, the market volatility, a number of "CAIJING" reporters interviewed by Wall Street people said that after the closing bell on March 3, the fund managers a common question is, now what to do?

Financial Services COMPANYB. Riley FBR inc. . Markets expected the Fed to cut interest rates, Mark Guerrant, chief global strategist and managing director, told Caijing, but the unexpected drop of 50 basis points, and the fact that we are now close to zero, suggests that the Fed has little policy space left. Now the market needs to be cautious, very cautious.

A major factor in the market's reluctance is that the epidemic is the main cause of unconventional interest rate cuts. WHO DIRECTOR-GENERAL TAN DESAI says the agency is most concerned about outbreaks in South Korea, Italy, Iran and Japan. He says the new coronavirus has a unique ability to spread from community to community, but with the right measures, the outbreak can be controlled. But "we are in uncharted territory, " tamdesay stresses.

Andorra, the Czech Republic, Indonesia, Jordan, Latvia, Portugal, Tunisia, Saudi Arabia and Senegal have all confirmed cases for the first time in their countries. Italy's new coronavirus epidemic continues to spread, the government said it may increase the number of quarantined areas to strengthen virus quarantine.

Twenty-seven people have died from new coronavirus infections in Italy in the past 24 hours, bringing the number of new coronavirus deaths in Italy to 79, according to the country's Civil Protection Agency. This is the northern region of Lombardy and the Veneto region 12 days ago since the outbreak of the death toll increased the most.

The U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) reported Wednesday that there have been 118 confirmed cases of new pneumonia in the United States, including 9 deaths. All the deaths came from Washington state. Disinfection of schools and subways is under way in the United States, and Vaccine Development is accelerating. "We have entered a new phase of the epidemic, " said Dow Constantin Gâlcă, the governor of King County, Washington. Six deaths in the United States have occurred in this state. Constantin Gâlcă said King County had acquired a hospital to treat patients in isolation.

G7 finance ministers and central bank governors are prepared to take action, including fiscal tools, at the necessary time to deal with the impact of the new pneumonia outbreak, the Treasury Department said in a statement posted on its website on March 3. But the G7 did not provide precise operational details.

'It's a tug of war between hope and fear, ' says Vasu Menon, senior investment strategist at Chinese Singaporean wealth management. Central banks are hopeful about potential stimulus, he said: "The question is what will they do? Monetary policy is already very loose, interest rates are very low. "

Wang Zhou, founding partner of QQQ capital, a hedge fund, told Caijing that the market had long anticipated and digested the Fed rate cut, which was sold today when the news was officially announced. The overall market sentiment affected by the epidemic, very low, risk-aversion dominated. The 10-year bond yields below 1% are evidence of this.

The Australian Central Bank was the first to cut rates before the Fed's easing. On March 3rd the RBA cut interest rates by 25 basis points to 0.50 per cent, a new low for Australia.

Australia's central bank also cut interest rates in response to the outbreak, saying an overseas coronavirus outbreak is having a significant impact on the Australian economy, particularly in the areas of education and tourism, gDP growth in the march quarter is likely to be significantly lower than previously expected. Following in the footsteps of the RBA, the Bank of Malaysia also cut interest rates, cutting its overnight policy rate by 25 basis points to 2.50 per cent.

The new outbreak of coronary pneumonia has raised concerns among investors about the economic impact. Harriman, Global Head of foreign exchange strategy at English surname Brothers Harriman, told Caijing that we will see more information on the Fed's decision in the next two weeks. But the Fed's move caused panic, especially as there was no clear sign of financial stability that such urgent action was needed.

The market still has a 68.6 percent chance of a further 25 basis point cut in April to 0.75 percent to 1.00 percent, according to the CME fed's instruments.
